85","1472":"1472","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","1 June 1438":"1 juni 1438","1412":"1412","1398":"1398","1441":"1441","about 1412":"circa 1412","about 1410":"circa 1410","about 1441":"circa 1441","1438":"1438","Lydeard St Lawrence, Somerset, England":"Lydeard St Lawrence, Somerset, England","England":"England","Dunster, Somerset, England":"Dunster, Somerset, England"},"en":{"about 1380–about 1441":"about 1380–about 1441","1385–Female":"1385–Deceased","1398–1438":"1398–1438","1412–1472":"1412–1472","1380–1441":"1380–1441","about 1380":"about 1380","1385":"1385","1472":"1472","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","1 June 1438":"1 June 1438","1412":"1412","1398":"1398","1441":"1441","about 1412":"about 1412","about 1410":"about 1410","about 1441":"about 1441","1438":"1438","Lydeard St Lawrence, Somerset, England":"Lydeard St Lawrence, Somerset, England","England":"England","Dunster, Somerset, England":"Dunster, Somerset, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Coker","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["see   Cocker  .","habitational name from a group of villages in Somerset named with Coker, from a Celtic river name meaning ‘crooked’.","English (southeastern):"],"variants":[{"name":"Coaker","meanings":["English (Devon): variant of   Coker  ."]},{"name":"Cocker","meanings":["English (Yorkshire and Lancashire): nickname for a quarrelsome person, from Middle English <i>coker</i> ‘fighter, wrangler’.","English: occupational name, ‘one who puts up hay in cocks’, a seasonal occupation.","Probably an Americanized form of German   Kocher  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":2,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Robert Coker was born about 1380, in Lydeard St Lawrence, Somerset, England. He married Joan Wallys about 1410. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died about 1441, in England, at the age of 63."},"et":{"about 1380–about 1441":"umbes 1380–umbes 1441","1385–Female":"1385–Surnud","1398–1438":"1398–1438","1412–1472":"1412–1472","1380–1441":"1380–1441","about 1380":"umbes 1380","1385":"1385","1472":"1472","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","1 June 1438":"1. juuni 1438","1412":"1412","1398":"1398","1441":"1441","about 1412":"umbes 1412","about 1410":"umbes 1410","about 1441":"umbes 1441","1438":"1438","Lydeard St Lawrence, Somerset, England":"Lydeard St Lawrence, Somerset, England","England":"England","Dunster, Somerset, England":"Dunster, Somerset, England"},"fi":{"about 1380–about 1441":"noin 1380–noin 1441","1385–Female":"1385–Kuollut","1398–1438":"1398–1438","1412–1472":"141